    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "OEE Overview",
            Slug = "oee-overview",
            Summary = "What Overall Equipment Effectiveness is, the three factors (Availability x Performance x Quality), world-class benchmarks, the Six Big Losses, and how to read the OEE dashboard.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/oee"]""",
            Tags = """["oee","manufacturing","metrics"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## OEE Overview\n\nOEE (**Overall Equipment Effectiveness**) is the single most widely used metric for how well a manufacturing operation runs. It compresses three independent questions into one number: *Is the machine running when it should be? Is it running as fast as it should? Is it making good parts?* The OEE module computes this per **work center** over a date range you choose, and shows you not just the score but where the losses are hiding.\n\n### The OEE Formula\n\nOEE is the product of three factors, each a ratio between 0 and 1 (shown as a percentage):\n\n**OEE = Availability x Performance x Quality**\n\nBecause the three are multiplied, OEE is always lower than its lowest factor. A machine that is 90% available, 90% performing, and 90% quality is only 0.9 x 0.9 x 0.9 = 72.9% effective — the losses compound.\n\n### Factor 1 — Availability\n\nAvailability answers: *did the machine run when it was scheduled to?* It is run time divided by available time. Available time is the **scheduled minutes** minus **planned downtime** (breaks, planned maintenance). Anything that stops the machine when it should be running — breakdowns, unplanned downtime, long setups — costs Availability.\n\n`Availability = Run Time Minutes / Available Minutes`\n\n### Factor 2 — Performance\n\nPerformance answers: *did the machine run as fast as it should have while it was running?* It compares the ideal cycle time (the theoretical fastest time per part) times the total parts produced against the actual run time. Small stops, idling, and reduced speed all drag Performance down. Performance can never legitimately exceed 100% — if it does, the ideal cycle time is set too slow.\n\n`Performance = (Ideal Cycle Time x Total Quantity) / Run Time`\n\n### Factor 3 — Quality\n\nQuality answers: *how many of the parts produced were good?* It is good quantity divided by total quantity. Scrap and rework both reduce Quality — a part that has to be reworked was not made right the first time.\n\n`Quality = Good Quantity / Total Quantity`\n\n### World-Class OEE\n\nA work center is flagged **world-class** when it hits the recognized benchmark — broadly, 85% OEE, which corresponds roughly to ~90% Availability, ~95% Performance, and ~99% Quality. Most operations start well below this; 60% is typical for a shop that has not been measuring, and even small improvements compound quickly because of the multiplication. The dashboard counts how many of your work centers are world-class.\n\n### The Six Big Losses\n\nEvery point of OEE you lose maps to one of six classic loss categories, grouped by the factor they hurt. The OEE detail panel breaks the lost minutes down across all six:\n\n**Availability losses**\n- **Equipment Failure** — breakdowns and unplanned stops.\n- **Setup & Adjustment** — changeover time, tooling changes, warm-up.\n\n**Performance losses**\n- **Idling & Minor Stops** — short stoppages, jams, blocked or starved conditions.\n- **Reduced Speed** — running slower than the ideal cycle time.\n\n**Quality losses**\n- **Process Defects** — scrap and defects produced during steady-state running.\n- **Reduced Yield** — defects produced during startup, warm-up, or after a changeover.\n\nThe six losses sum to the total lost minutes, and seeing which category dominates tells you exactly where to focus improvement effort.\n\n### Reading the Dashboard\n\nThe OEE page opens on a **work-center grid** — one card per work center, each showing its OEE gauge, the three factors, and counts (total, good, scrap). A star badge marks world-class centers. The toolbar shows the **average OEE** across all centers and a **world-class count**. Pick a date range with the period selector (Last 30 Days, This Month, This Week). Select a card to open the **detail panel**, which shows an **OEE Trend** chart (Availability, Performance, Quality, and OEE over time — switchable between Daily, Weekly, and Monthly granularity) and a **Six Big Losses** breakdown.\n\n### How OEE Connects to the Rest of QB Engineer\n\nOEE is computed from production data — run time, downtime, and produced quantities flow from jobs, production runs, and quality records. **Scrap and rework** quantities come from QC and production reporting; **downtime** comes from machine and clock events. The work centers themselves are the assets/equipment you run jobs on. OEE doesn't change any of that data — it's a read-only analytical view over it.\n\n### When to Use OEE\n\n- To find your worst-performing work center and the single factor dragging it down\n- To decide whether to invest in uptime (Availability), speed (Performance), or scrap reduction (Quality)\n- To track whether an improvement actually moved the number, via the trend chart\n- To benchmark against the world-class 85% target\n- To translate vague 'the machine is slow' complaints into a specific loss category","sections":[]}"""
        });

